{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489514","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489514"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:19:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:19:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"676"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"676","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/676"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.34,0.1,0.09,0.39]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"676"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90556"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"676","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/676"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"676"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74774"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1886"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5369"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1396"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1412"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7946"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10701"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11056"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11057"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16363"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30211"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30241"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43032"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44758"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90556","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90556"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 53-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of persistent cough. He has a 30 pack-year smoking history and continues to smoke. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He works as a carpenter and has no relevant travel history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Respiratory examination reveals normal breath sounds with no added sounds. A low-dose screening CT of the chest reveals a solitary pulmonary nodule measuring 6mm in diameter adjacent to the bifurcation of the right pulmonary arteries. The nodule has smooth margins and no calcification. No other abnormalities are detected.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Surgical resection","Fine-needle aspiration biopsy","Positron emission tomography scan","Chest radiograph in six months","Computed tomography surveillance"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe management of incidentally detected pulmonary nodules is guided by the Fleischner Society guidelines, which consider nodule size, morphology, and patient risk factors. This patient has a 6mm solid nodule and is considered high-risk due to his significant smoking history. The small size and adjacency to the pulmonary vessels make this lesion high risk for biopsy or surgical resection, and even without memorising the Fleischner criteria, these factors should make a clinician hesitant to pursue invasive options. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComputed tomography surveillance\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management according to the Fleischner Society guidelines. For a solid nodule measuring 6mm in a high-risk patient, the recommendation is follow-up CT at 6-12 months, then consideration of another CT at 18-24 months if no change. This approach allows monitoring for growth or changes in nodule characteristics while avoiding unnecessary invasive procedures for what may be a benign finding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical resection\u003C/strong\u003E is overly aggressive for a 6mm nodule without suspicious features. According to the Fleischner guidelines, resection is typically considered for larger nodules (\u0026gt;8mm) with concerning features, rapid growth on serial imaging, or high suspicion of malignancy based on other investigations. The risk of surgical complications outweighs the benefit for this small nodule.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFine-needle aspiration biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended for nodules smaller than 8mm due to technical challenges and high false-negative rates. The proximity to pulmonary vessels further increases the risk of complications such as pneumothorax or hemorrhage. The Fleischner guidelines suggest biopsy only for larger nodules or when there are highly suspicious features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPositron emission tomography scan\u003C/strong\u003E has limited utility for  smaller nodules (e.g.less than 10mm) due to false-negative results from limited spatial resolution and lower metabolic activity in small lesions. The Fleischner guidelines do not recommend PET scanning for nodules of this size, regardless of risk status.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChest radiograph in six months\u003C/strong\u003E is inadequate for surveillance of small pulmonary nodules. A 6mm nodule may not be visible on chest radiography, and subtle changes in size or morphology would be difficult to detect. The Fleischner guidelines specifically recommend CT rather than chest radiography for nodule follow-up due to its superior sensitivity and ability to characterize nodules.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to CT surveillance, smoking cessation counseling should be provided to this patient given his ongoing smoking and significant pack-year history. This is an essential component of comprehensive management that can reduce his risk of developing lung cancer and other smoking-related diseases.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Repeat CT scans at intervals of 3 to 6 months are essential for monitoring solitary pulmonary nodules, enabling clinicians to assess stability, growth, or changes in appearance, thus guiding further management decisions","The Fleischner Society guidelines provide evidence-based recommendations for the follow-up and management of incidentally discovered pulmonary nodules based on size, morphology, and patient risk factors","Solitary pulmonary nodules less than 8mm in diameter generally do not warrant immediate invasive procedures like biopsy or surgical resection in patients without concerning clinical features","Smoking cessation counseling is an essential component of management for patients with pulmonary nodules, particularly those with significant smoking history"],"references":["The National Lung Screening Trial Research Team. Reduced Lung-Cancer Mortality with Low-Dose Computed Tomographic Screening. N Engl J Med. 2011; 365: 395-409.","MacMahon H, Naidich DP, Goo HM, Lee KS, Leung ANC, Mayo JR, Mehta AC, Ohno Y, Powell CA, Prokop M, Rubin GD, Schaefer-Prokop CM, Travis WD, Can Schil PE, Bankier AA. Guidelines for Management of Incidental Pulmonary Nodules Detected on CT Images: From the Fleischner Society 2017. Radiology. 2017; 284(1).","Winokur RS, Pua BB, Sullivan BW, Madoff DC. Percutaneous lung biopsy: technique, efficacy, and complications. Semin Intervent Radiol. 2013 Jun;30(2):121-7. doi: 10.1055/s-0033-1342952. PMID: 24436527; PMCID: PMC3709987."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74774"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"676"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74774","links":{"s